DNS query testing commands
==============================

1. dig (Domain Information Groper)
====================================

dig is an advanced DNS troubleshooting tool
gives detailed DNS response
mostly used by Linux admins


dig is an advanced DNS troubleshooting tool
gives detailed DNS response
mostly used by Linux admins

Command:1
dig google.com

what it does:
queries default DNS server
resolves google.com → IP address

Output shows:
QUESTION SECTION  → what you asked
ANSWER SECTION    → IP address (A record)
AUTHORITY SECTION → authoritative DNS
ADDITIONAL        → extra DNS info

Command:2
dig google.com @8.8.8.8

What it does:
queries specific DNS server (8.8.8.8 – Google DNS)
bypasses local DNS (/etc/resolv.conf)
used to test external DNS


Command:3
dig google.com +short

What it does:
shows only IP address
hides extra DNS details


2.nslookup (legacy but common)
=================================
older DNS query tool
still available in all Linux systems
simple output


Command:1
nslookup google.com

What it does:
queries default DNS server
resolves hostname → IP

Output shows:
DNS server used
resolved IP address

Command:2
nslookup google.com 8.8.8.8

What it does:
queries specific DNS server (8.8.8.8)
ignores local DNS configuration


3.host (simple & fast)
=====================
basic DNS lookup tool
minimal output
easy to read

command :
host google.com

What it does:
resolves hostname → IP address
shows A / AAAA records


note:
dig       → advanced DNS analysis
nslookup → basic DNS testing
host     → quick hostname resolution

